      "desc": "PHerc. Paris 4 is a rolled Herculaneum papyrus from the [Institut de France](https://www.institutdefrance.fr/en/home/), carbonized during the eruption of Mount Vesuvius in 79 AD. It was first scanned at the [Diamond Light Source](https://www.diamond.ac.uk) in Oxfordshire, UK (2023, at 7.91 µm), and rescanned in 2026 at the [ESRF](https://www.esrf.fr) in Grenoble, France (2.4 µm, plus 45.5 µm overview scans).\n\nIt is the scroll with by far the most segments, and the first from which substantial continuous Greek text — Epicurean philosophy attributed to Philodemus — was recovered: the [first letters](https://scrollprize.org/firstletters) were discovered here, and the [2023 Grand Prize](https://scrollprize.org/grandprize) was claimed on it."
    },
