      "desc": "PHerc. 332 is a rolled Herculaneum papyrus from the [Biblioteca Nazionale di Napoli](https://www.bnnonline.it/it/121/officina-dei-papiri-ercolanesi), carbonized during the eruption of Mount Vesuvius in 79 AD. It was first scanned at the [Diamond Light Source](https://www.diamond.ac.uk) in Oxfordshire, UK (2023, at 3.24 µm and 7.91 µm), and rescanned at 2.4 µm at the [ESRF](https://www.esrf.fr) in Grenoble, France (2025).\n\nIt is the innermost part of a scroll, known as a *midollo* (marrow), a remnant from physical unwrapping of the larger original. Its small size is what made such high-resolution scans practical.",
